@page
@model new_site.Pages.the_sugar_industryModel
@{
    Layout = "_LayoutA";
}

<div style="background-color: white; padding:1vw">
    <div class="title-container" style="border-color: rgb(61, 91, 179); margin-bottom:2vw;">
        <p class="title" style="color:rgb(68, 105, 93); font-size:2vw">The Sugar Industry</p>
    </div>
    <div style="width:63%; margin:auto;">
        <p class="research-text">
            The sugar industry is a vast global network that transforms raw crops into one of the most widely used ingredients in the modern diet.
            From the fields where sugarcane and sugar beets are grown to the factories where they’re processed, refined, and packaged,
            sugar production is a massive operation involving agriculture, chemistry, and international trade. It fuels economies, employs millions,
            and supports countless products beyond just food — including medicine, cosmetics, and even biofuels.
        </p>
        <div style="background-color:rgb(61, 91, 179);padding:1vw;">
            <p class="research-text" style="color:white;">
                Like many industries tied to food production, it has been the focus of both praise and criticism. Supporters point to its role in economic development
                and food preservation, while critics raise concerns about environmental impact, labor practices, and the global rise in sugar consumption.
            </p>
        </div>
        <p class="research-text">
            Despite ongoing debate, the sugar industry remains a powerful force, adapting to changing health guidelines and public demand through innovation and regulation.
            Understanding the industry means looking not just at the product itself, but at the systems behind how it’s grown, refined, and delivered to our tables.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>
